[2]
Date: Tue, 21 Aug 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Daily Monitor, Kampala, 21 Aug 2006 [edited]
<http://www.monitor.co.ug/news/news082111.php>

In the districts of Masaka, Rakai and Sembabule, 42 suspects have been
arrested over illegal transportation of cattle from quarantined areas
between June and August.
Addressing journalists in Rakai on 14 Aug 2006, the Southern Regional
Police Commander, Mr Assuman Mugenyi, said 152 head of cattle were impounded.
He said 17 vehicles, 117 goats, 48 pigs and 18 sheep were also impounded.
Mugenyi said more than 4400 hides and skins were also confiscated.
The Agriculture Ministry imposed a quarantine on livestock in the districts
of Rakai, Isingiro, Ntungamo, Mbarara, Masaka, Mpigi, Kampala and Mukono.
[Map at <http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/uganda.pdf>].
Others are Bushenyi, Luweero, Nakaseke, Kiboga, Mubende, Kabale, Kasese and
Kitgum. This followed an outbreak of the FMD in the districts.
On 2 Aug 2006, the Parliament passed a motion authorising the government to
incur additional expenditure of Shs 4.5 billion [USD 2 435 065 ] for
emergency control and eradication of the FMD that is threatening to engulf
the country.
Finance State Minister Jachan Omach said there was "emergency pressure"
that required immediate purchase of at least 2 million doses of the vaccine
to contain the disease in the affected districts and surrounding areas.
He warned that if the disease spreads near Entebbe International Airport, a
ban might be slammed on international flights.
[Byline: Aliga Issa]
